---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="phone is cigarette for the brain — hkg">
  <main class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6">
    <div class="mb-10">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-white">
        phone is cigarette for the brain
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-neutral-500">most people are a lot more interesting than they think they are</p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-10 text-base text-neutral-300 leading-relaxed">

      <div class="space-y-5">
        <p>
          I'll take an interesting angle here because I want to hope that most of anyone reading
          this can recognize what phone addiction looks like and acknowledges that it's very harmful.
          But just in case you didn't know that, yep, phone addiction is the most harmful addiction
          you might face in your entire life.
        </p>
        <p>
          I think it's pretty evident when you have habits like checking your phone immediately after
          waking up, opening apps without intending to, pulling out your phone during a 10 second
          wait, or being unable to sit in silence.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-5">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">it's your fault. kind of.</h2>
        <p>
          I want to frame it in a way where you don't see it as your fault, because yeah, the apps
          are designed for retention and engagement. But in the ways that matter, it's your fault.
          I imagine it would be pretty difficult to change how those apps are designed, so what's left
          is changing how you use them. Which should be less.
        </p>
        <p>
          Here is a little list of things you lose out on when you consume too much of that online
          content:
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 pl-2">
          {["attention span", "presence", "boredom", "curiosity", "deep conversation", "real-world observation", "patience"].map((item) => (
            <li class="flex gap-3">
              <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-neutral-600" />
              <span>{item}</span>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
        <p>
          I genuinely think some people have not been alone with their own thoughts in years.
          The scariest part is that this behavior is completely socially acceptable now.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-5">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">ask yourself why.</h2>
        <p>
          There is a reason why you do this. The reason you do anything is because you prefer it
          over the alternatives. Your brain believes checking it is more rewarding than whatever
          alternative exists in that moment. More rewarding than boredom. More rewarding than
          silence. More rewarding than just sitting there thinking.
        </p>
        <p>
          And with that you lose opportunities. You lose the thought that would've shown up if you
          stayed bored for just a little longer. You lose the random idea that only comes when your
          brain finally runs out of noise. You lose the slight shift in mood that happens when you
          actually sit with what you're feeling instead of escaping it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-5">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">personality is something you build.</h2>
        <p>
          I think most people underestimate how much personality is something you build, not
          something you just have. Like yeah, there's a baseline version of you, temperament,
          instincts, whatever. But a huge part of who you actually become is shaped by what you
          repeatedly expose yourself to, what you spend time doing, and what you practice being.
        </p>
        <p>
          And this is where it gets interesting with phones. Because if most of your input is
          consumption, scrolling, watching, reacting, then you're basically training yourself
          to exist as an observer of life instead of a participant in it. Which is fine if that's
          your goal, but I really don't think it is.
        </p>
        <p>
          You get a lot of content, a lot of opinions, a lot of personalities to look at, but
          not a lot of space to develop your own. And I want to emphasize that space. We need
          space to create our personalities.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-5">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">start small.</h2>
        <p>
          I'm not going to say you need to delete every app, wake up at 5am, take cold showers,
          and become some ultra-disciplined productivity machine. I think it starts much smaller
          than that. Just prove to yourself that you still own your attention.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2.5 pl-2">
          {[
            "Leave your phone in another room for a little while.",
            "Take a drive without instantly needing stimulation.",
            "Stand in line without grabbing your phone like a reflex.",
            "Go eat with your friends and actually stay present for the conversation.",
          ].map((item) => (
            <li class="flex gap-3">
              <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-neutral-600" />
              <span>{item}</span>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
        <p>
          Give your brain a chance to be bored again. Baby steps are the key to building a better
          future for yourself. (read that in a very motivating and powerful tone)
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-5">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">so what do you do with the space.</h2>
        <p>
          Once you have that space, go try something new. It's expected and even beneficial to be
          bad at it to begin with. Every interesting person you've ever met probably spent years
          being unbelievably mediocre at the thing that eventually became part of who they are.
        </p>
        <p>I think creating starts a lot smaller than people imagine.</p>
        <p>Follow whatever naturally pulls your attention when nobody is watching.</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2.5 pl-2">
          {[
            "Write even if it's terrible.",
            "Take photos of random things.",
            "Learn an instrument badly.",
            "Cook complicated meals for no reason.",
            "Read things that challenge your worldview.",
            "Build weird projects that only make sense to you.",
            "Let your curiosity get the best of you even if it leads nowhere in the end.",
          ].map((item) => (
            <li class="flex gap-3">
              <span class="mt-2 h-1.5 w-1.5 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-neutral-600" />
              <span>{item}</span>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
        <p>
          Not everything needs to become a side hustle or personal brand or optimized source of
          income. Some things should exist simply because they make you feel alive. Because isn't
          that the point.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-5">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white">the harder argument.</h2>
        <p>
          There's a version of this argument that goes: the phone is just a tool, and tools aren't
          the problem, it's how you use them. This is true and also slightly dishonest, because these
          particular tools are designed with the explicit goal of maximizing the time you spend using
          them. They are not neutral.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm not asking you to be perfect. I'm asking you to be a little more intentional about
          something that's quietly consuming enormous portions of your life, attention, and personality.
          And decide whether the exchange is actually worth it. Most of us, if we're being honest,
          would say it isn't.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-xl bg-white p-6 text-neutral-900 font-medium">
        Put the phone down. Look up. Something interesting is probably happening right in front of you.
      </div>

    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
